# Poly is a programming language that is used to create complex machines in a
# simple and composable way.  Poly is inspired by the mathematics of polynomial
# functors and natural transformations between them (see for more:
# https://arxiv.org/pdf/2312.00990).

# In Poly, you can build a system by first declaring all of its interfaces and
# then declaring how those interfaces are related.  A (polynomial) interface is
# a collection of states, and then a collection of possible actions for each
# state.  For example, we could have the following interface where the actions
# one can perform on a machine dependent on its state.
interface Car
    On { Drive, TurnOff },
    Off { TurnOn }

# In Poly, we are building a system by declaring all of its components and the
# relationships between those components.  The system can then by executed by
# making a query, which would typically be done through a CLI.  Hence, Poly is
# not a language that has an inherent model of execution, it is simply
# specifying a machine through declaring it's interfaces and the relationships
# between them.

# The main usage of Poly is to be embedded in a Rust application.  A Poly script
# is interpreted in some form, and then through a Rust API the compiled machine
# can be queried and rendered reactively.  This means that the Rust program will
# provide data to, and use, the outward facing interfaces declared by the Poly
# script.  This also means Rust can handle any platform specific or compute
# intense aspects of the program (e.g. graphics, file system duties, etc).

# Though the goal is to interoperate with Rust, the Poly language itself is
# flexible enough to be embedded within any platform.

# There is built-in support for (simple, non-recursive) algebraic data types.  All data is immutable
# in poly as there is not inherent notion of reference.
schema User
    username: String,
    password: String,
    age: Int

# Interfaces can also define a state machine by declaring how actions correspond
# to state transitions.  This interface has a state for each integer `n`, and
# the actions `Increment` and `Decrement` map to new states.  When states are
# parameterized, actions can also be guarded with a predicate.
interface Counter
    Count[n: Int] {
        Increment -> Count[n + 1],
        (n > 0) Decrement -> Count[n - 1]
    }

# There is a standard set of built-in polynomial interfaces to make getting
# started easier.  Below is a list of some examples, but could be expanded.
interface Option
    Some { Unwrap },
    None

interface Result
    Ok { Continue },
    Error { Handle }

view Ignore : Result -> Option
    Ok -> Some {
        Unwrap -> Continue
    },
    Err -> None

